=> At linux terminal we use cp command to copy files and directories.

=> The syntax of this command is:

    $ cp -vinr [...file/directory-sources] [destination]

Examples:
---------

-> How to copy a single file;
    $ cp file1.txt dir1/

-> How to copy multiple files:
    $ cp file1.txt file2.txt dir1/

-> How copy a directory:
    $ cp -r dir1/ dir2/

**** To copy directories, you have to pass the -r flag. This flag informs the cp command to recursively copy a directory and its contents.

-> How to copy files that match a glob pattern:
    $ cp dir1/*.txt dir2/

-> Copy files which are updated:
    $ cp -rvu dir1/ dir2/    //The 'u' option select only the updated files.
